244. hodie nate, i. e. you who are keeping your birthday to-day, cs. 164 nam mihi hodie natalis dies est, 178.

246. respice: respicere is used of looking back and shewing regard sor a person or thing, pitying thern. Cf. Verg. Ecl. 1. 28 Libertas quae sera tamen respexit inertem.

246. em, ‘look you, here are some people who want to talk to you.' Fleckeisen has est which may be defended as σχῆμα Πινδαρικόν, but this is rare in Latin.

248. qui sospitans etc. Ps. ‘A man who has been your salvation.' Ball. ‘Has been? then he's dead. I want a man who’s alive to be my salvation.’ With fuit supply sospitalis. Ballio says that however useful a man has been in the past he is as good as dead. For the sentiment cf. infr. 811, Truc. 166.

252. te uolo sc. conuenire or colloqui, cf. Cure. 391, 686, Trin. 516, 717, 963, 1059. paucis (sc. uerbis) is osten added. Here there is a play on words, continued in at uos ego ambos, as te uolo may also mean le Iouem perdere uolo.

256. Imaum, properly the frequentative of maneo, but almost if not entirely identical in meaning.
